'''Kevin Andrews''' is a [[Honolulu]]-based [[entrepreneur]] and [[Invention|inventor]]. He is the former president of the [[Waimānalo, Hawaii|Waimanalo]] [[Chamber of Commerce]]<ref name="Waimanalo firm envisions biotech incubator">{{Cite web |url= http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2002/May/31/ln/ln25a.html |publisher= The Honolulu Advertiser |title= Waimanalo firm envisions biotech incubator |accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref> and heads Plant Research Corp. and Hula Girls Foods, located in Waimanalo, Hawaii. 

Plant Research Corp., which includes subsidiaries Aloha Ardvaark Corp., a wastewater/agriculture waste management business, and Hawai'i Cytogenetics Inc., a [[Biotechnology|biotech]] company which researches methods for mass production of living [[plant]] [[Cell (biology)|cells]].<ref name="Waimanalo firm envisions biotech incubator"/><ref name="Waimanalo lab site available for biotech">{{Cite web |url= http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/stories/2001/07/02/smallb1.html?page=all |publisher= Pacific Business News |title= Waimanalo lab site available for biotech |accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref>

Andrews holds patents for novelty [[sugarcane]] products,<ref name="Patents by Inventor Kevin R. Andrews">{{Cite web |url= http://patents.justia.com/inventor/kevin-r-andrews |publisher= Justina.com |title= Patents by Inventor Kevin R. Andrews |accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref> which he manufactures using organic sugarcane and distributes through Hula Girl Foods. Its products are sold and used around the world, including by [[Distilled beverage|spirits]] manufacturer [[Bacardi]] and outlets in Hawaii such as [[ABC Stores (Hawaii)|ABC Stores]].<ref name="Adding A Little Swizzle To Your Cocktail">{{Cite web |url= http://archives.midweek.com/content/columns/tabletalk_article/adding_a_little_swizzle_to_your_cocktail/ |publisher= midweek.com |title= Adding A Little Swizzle To Your Cocktail |accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref> Hula Girl’s products include cane skewers, [[chopsticks]], cocktail sticks, [[coffee]] and [[tea]] stirrers and pupu skewers.

