{{orphan|date = February 2009}}

'''Multimarket contact''' occurs when [[company|firms]] meet the same rivals in multiple markets. When firms compete with each other in more than one [[Market (economics)|market]], their [[Competition|competitive behavior]] may differ from that of single-market rivals. Multimarket competition may result in the reduction of the competitive intensity among rivals, an effect known as mutual forbearance.

Multimarket contact gives a firm the option to respond to actions or attacks by a rival not only in the market being challenged, but also in other markets where they both compete. As a result, multimarket competitors may hesitate to attack in one market for fear of [[retaliation]] in other markets.

